<HEADLINE>
<P>
RICE NOT PERFECT FOOD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DR. NEIL SOLOMON, Neil Solomon is the author of Sick &amp; Tired of Being 
Sick &amp; Tired, Wynwood Press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Question: I enjoy watching the programs on public television that deal with the 
way people live in other parts of the world. It seems to me that in many 
countries, children are brought up on rice, if they're lucky, and little else. 
</P>
<P>
Is rice such a wonder food that it can provide everything a child needs in the 
way of a nutritious diet? 
</P>
<P>
Answer: Children who live almost entirely on rice do so out of necessity, not 
out of choice. In many cases, the alternative is not to eat at all. 
</P>
<P>
No single food can provide all of the child's nutritional needs, and rice is no 
exception. For example, rice provides almost no Vitamin A, which is essential 
for good vision. Children on all-rice diets who do not receive Vitamin A 
supplements are at risk of blindness. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA041990-0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 206354 </DOCID>
