<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: MOVIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By GREG BRAXTON, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Garbo Really Alone: Greta Garbo described herself in a 1926 letter as a lonely 
girl who was homesick for her native Sweden, according to a secret file opened 
by officials at Stockholm's Royal Library. 
</P>
<P>
"I live very lonely in a place where I am left absolutely alone, I go out for 
walks sometimes alone, look at the sky and the water and talk to myself," Garbo 
wrote from Hollywood to her actress friend, Vera Schmiterlov. The letter had a 
drawing of a crying girl, topped by the word "homesick." The 84-year-old 
reclusive star died in New York on Easter Sunday. GREG BRAXTON 
</P>
</TEXT>
