<P>
VATICAN, PRAGUE RESTORE TIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times wire services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
VATICAN CITY 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Vatican and Czechoslovakia restored diplomatic relations today in a move 
that expands the church's influence in the former Communist-dominated countries 
of Eastern Europe. 
</P>
<P>
The announcement of the resumption of ties after 40 years came two days before 
Pope John Paul II begins a historic visit to Czechoslovakia. 
</P>
<P>
Czechoslovakia, where the Roman Catholic Church was severely repressed for 
decades, is the latest in a series of Warsaw Pact countries to renew ties with 
the Vatican. The Pope's native Poland re-established diplomatic relations last 
year, followed by Hungary in February. A month ago, the Vatican and the Soviet 
Union established official ties for the first time since the Russian Revolution 
although they fall short of full diplomatic relations. 
</P>
